@@eThe Deltari: Readers of the Flow@@N

@@dFrom the oral archive of the Lower Kowloon Watercourse Guild,@@N
@@das transcribed by a sympathetic clerk who asked not to be named@@N

The river delta folk were in @@eKowloon@@N before it was Kowloon.
Before the first human merchant drove a post into the mud and called
it a dock, the Deltari had already mapped every channel, every tidal
pattern, every seasonal shift in the great river's mood. They built
the @@ehydraulic infrastructure@@N — the locks, the levees, the
drainage channels — that made the delta habitable. Generations
later, the city rose on their work and @@yforgot to mention it@@N.

They are amphibious-adapted: skin that sheds water like oiled silk,
eyes that see clearly in the murk beneath the surface, hearing
pitched to the low frequencies that travel through water and stone.
They move between river and land as easily as other folk move between
rooms. A Deltari underwater is not holding their breath — they are
@@ehome@@N.

Their gift and their burden is that they @@yread the flow@@N. Not
merely water — though water is where it begins. A Deltari learns
the current, and from the current learns to read @@epatterns@@N:
market fluctuations, information movement, the subtle shifts in
power that precede political change. They see systems the way a
river-pilot sees channels — as living things with direction, force,
and consequence.

The @@eJade Magistracy@@N of Kowloon excludes them from formal
civic power. This is well-documented, despite the Magistracy's
preference that it not be. The Deltari built the water systems.
The Magistracy depends on the water systems. The Deltari are not
permitted to hold magistral office. The contradiction is sustained
by the simple mechanism of @@rnot discussing it@@N.

But the Deltari maintain their own records. @@eFlow records@@N that
track the delta's changes over centuries. @@eOral genealogies@@N
passed down through family lines that the Magistracy's registries
do not acknowledge. And certain names — names from the @@rBlack
Ledger@@N, the sealed record of debts and decisions that Kowloon's
ruling families would prefer to keep submerged.

The official institutions cannot suppress what they cannot find.
The Deltari keep their parallel records in the water, in the
spoken word, in the current itself.

@@dThe river does not forget its course,@@N
@@dno matter how many walls you build across it.@@N
